m the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Essen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: habitational name from any of several places called Essen, for example in the Ruhr.","English: variant of   Esson   (see   Easton  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Esson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans.","Scottish (Aberdeenshire): from a shortened and altered form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Adamh</i> (see   Adam  ). This surname was sometimes confused with 2 below.","English and Scottish: variant of   Easton  , although in some instances the Scottish surname may reflect the reverse process, in which the name in 1 above has acquired an intrusive <i>-t-</i>."]},{"name":"Essman","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Essmann</b>: habitational name, a variant of   Essen  , with the suffix <i>man</i> ‘man’ or nickname for a big eater, from the agent derivative of Middle High German <i>ezzen</i> ‘to eat’."]}]},{"name":"Hendrik","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Henrik ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1356696,"age":16,"year":"1506","julianDay":2271115,"description":"The Netherlands is inherited by the future Habsburg Emperor and King of Spain Charles V.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1356697,"age":26,"year":"1516","julianDay":2274767,"description":"The Catholic King Charles I of Spain ruled the Netherlands.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1356698,"age":82,"year":"1572","julianDay":2295221,"description":"William of Orange was recognized as viceroy of Holland, Friesland and Utrecht.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1356699,"age":83,"year":"1573","julianDay":2295587,"description":"The siege of Leiden between the rebels and the Spanish. 1574 The dikes were opened allowing a Dutch fleet to sail over the flood waters and rescue Leiden.","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"Hendrik van Essen was born in 1490, in Twello, Voorst, Gelderland, Netherlands. He married Barbara van de Padevoirt in 1527. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1579, in Netherlands, at the age of 89."},"et":{"1490–1579":"1490–1579","1499–1564":"1499–1564","1520–Male":"1520–Surnud","1528–1600":"1528–1600","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1499":"1499","1520":"1520","1564":"1564","1573":"1573","1572":"1572","1490":"1490","1528":"1528","1506":"1506","1527":"1527","1516":"1516","Netherlands":"Madalmaad","Twello, Voorst, Gelderland, Netherlands":"Twello, Voorst, Gelderland, Madalmaad"},"fi":{"1490–1579":"1490–1579","1499–1564":"1499–1564","1520–Male":"1520–Kuollut","1528–1600":"1528–1600","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1499":"1499","1520":"1520","1564":"1564","1573":"1573","1572":"1572","1490":"1490","1528":"1528","1506":"1506","1527":"1527","1516":"1516","Netherlands":"Alankomaat","Twello, Voorst, Gelderland, Netherlands":"Twello, Voorst, Gelderland, Alankomaat"},"fr":{"1490–1579":"1490–1579","1499–1564":"1499–1564","1520–Male":"1520–Décédé","1528–1600":"1528–1600","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1499":"1499","1520":"1520","1564":"1564","1573":"1573","1572":"1572","1490":"